<i># The count #</i>

36:42.583 --> 36:44.375
Yes, we've met.

36:50.250 --> 36:51.708
Orphans...

36:51.792 --> 36:53.250
this is my theater troupe.

36:53.333 --> 36:54.542
- Hi.
- Hi.

36:54.625 --> 36:56.292
- Hi.
- Hello.

36:56.375 --> 37:00.333
And as anyone in the theater knows,
after a grand entrance,

37:00.417 --> 37:03.042
the audience is supposed to applaud.

37:03.125 --> 37:04.625
"Applaud" means go like this.

37:05.667 --> 37:07.125
We're not an audience.

37:07.208 --> 37:11.042
No, orphans, you are not.

37:11.125 --> 37:15.167
But we have been preparing
an exciting new production

37:15.250 --> 37:18.250
that, on opening night,
will change your life.

37:18.333 --> 37:23.042
All of the artistic and financial aspects
of my career are finally coming together

37:23.125 --> 37:26.708
like two pieces of a bread
in the middle of a sandwich.

37:27.039 --> 37:29.039
Bread goes on the outside of a
sandwich.

37:29.750 --> 37:31.292
What my sister means is that...

37:31.375 --> 37:32.667
I don't care what she means.

37:32.750 --> 37:34.542
I don't have time to learn
a second language

37:34.625 --> 37:36.750
besides whatever it is
I'm speaking right now.

37:36.833 --> 37:40.833
In any case,
we demand congratulations.

37:42.500 --> 37:44.208
Congratulations.

37:45.708 --> 37:47.167
A big round of applause.

37:50.708 --> 37:54.250
And the delicious meal that you promised
myself and my troupe.

37:54.646 --> 37:56.646
We need a few minutes, you scoundrel.

37:56.875 --> 37:58.583
You know, every time she talks,

37:58.667 --> 38:01.708
it's like the tines of a fork
are being jammed into my...

38:01.792 --> 38:03.708
What my sister means is,
dinner will be served shortly.

38:03.792 --> 38:05.083
What are we supposed to do until then?

38:05.167 --> 38:08.417
- We could wait patiently.
- How about some wine, Olaf?

38:08.500 --> 38:10.625
Yes, yes, wine.
We had that nice rose last time.

38:10.708 --> 38:12.750
It wasn't rose, it was just watered down.

38:13.292 --> 38:15.875
Okay, fine.
I'll open up a box of the Merlot.

38:25.833 --> 38:29.375
An associate of mine
named Brillat-Savarin famously said:

38:29.458 --> 38:33.375
"To invite people to dine with us
is to make ourselves responsible

38:33.458 --> 38:36.167
<i>for their well-being
as long as they are under our roofs."</i>

38:36.875 --> 38:39.833
<i>But he was an 18th century philosopher
and gourmand...</i>

38:41.167 --> 38:44.583
<i>and these were three children
with very little catering experience.</i>

38:49.958 --> 38:53.583
Nevertheless, the Baudelaire orphans
snapped into action.

38:53.667 --> 38:57.042
This pasta maker reminds me
of the one built by Thomas Jefferson.

38:57.125 --> 38:58.125
Will it work?

38:59.333 --> 39:01.250
It will now.

39:01.333 --> 39:03.542
I wonder if Count Olaf's troupe
will enjoy this meal.

39:03.625 --> 39:05.750
Mother said that actors will eat anything.

39:06.208 --> 39:08.875
You've seen them perform.
Would you call them actors?

39:08.958 --> 39:11.250
They're all as talented as Count Olaf.

39:11.333 --> 39:13.125
<i>While they waited
for the pasta to boil,</i>

39:13.208 --> 39:16.000
<i>Violet sauteed the garlic,
and washed and chopped the anchovies.</i>

39:16.083 --> 39:18.583
<i>Klaus peeled the tomatoes
and pitted the olives.</i>

39:18.667 --> 39:20.292
And Sunny banged on a pot
with a wooden spoon,

39:20.375 --> 39:23.458
singing a rather repetitive song
she had written herself.

39:26.375 --> 39:28.458
By the time it was time
for the youngest Baudelaire

39:28.542 --> 39:30.125
to chop the parsley with her teeth...

39:32.708 --> 39:35.792
all three children felt less miserable
than they had...

39:36.292 --> 39:38.625
<i>since they first came to Count Olaf's.</i>

39:38.708 --> 39:40.958
I think Dad would be proud of this sauce.

39:41.042 --> 39:44.083
And I think Mom would be proud
of how you made your own pasta.

39:44.583 --> 39:47.542
Maybe we can make this our home after all.

39:48.458 --> 39:51.042
Remember what Father said
when he burnt the quesadillas?

39:51.125 --> 39:52.167
Yeah.

39:53.292 --> 39:54.375
"Better than nothing."

39:58.583 --> 40:03.042
At times like these,
surrounded by colleagues and cohorts,

40:03.125 --> 40:07.167
gathered in fellowship
for the purpose of plotting theater,

40:07.250 --> 40:10.875
there's an eternal question
that always springs to mind...

40:11.833 --> 40:14.625
WHEN ARE WE GOING TO EAT?

40:18.958 --> 40:20.125
Dinner is served.

40:20.208 --> 40:23.125
- Wow, that was quick.
- And it smells delicious.

40:23.208 --> 40:25.500
I mean...

40:27.000 --> 40:31.125
As I was saying,
before the help interrupted...

40:32.750 --> 40:35.583
there is no "I" in acting...

40:36.208 --> 40:39.542
no selfish urges, no arrogance,

40:39.625 --> 40:42.333
no ego, no vanity,

40:42.417 --> 40:46.792
no dangerous overabundance
of inflated self-regard.

40:47.708 --> 40:52.792
There is only what the French call
a certain... <i>"escargot"</i>.

40:52.875 --> 40:53.958
Mmm-hmm.

40:54.042 --> 40:58.250
It is the first burst of applause
when the curtain rises.

40:58.333 --> 41:01.000
The second burst of applause

41:01.083 --> 41:04.958
when the leading man
glides out from the wings,

41:05.042 --> 41:09.458
faces his crowd and recites the...

41:09.542 --> 41:11.250
Soliloquy.

41:12.833 --> 41:16.417
I'm... That's... His soliloquy.

41:17.333 --> 41:21.542
It is the thrill of the 14th mandatory
standing ovation.

41:22.417 --> 41:26.042
I give and I give to my public

41:26.125 --> 41:30.458
just as I give and I give
to these orphans.

41:30.542 --> 41:33.625
But sometimes,
and every actor does this,

41:33.708 --> 41:36.125
I ask myself, "Is it worth it?

41:36.625 --> 41:39.833
Is it really worth it to chase
an enormous fortune?"

41:39.917 --> 41:41.250
Boss...

41:44.042 --> 41:45.917
- Where's the roast beef?
- What?

41:48.833 --> 41:51.417
The roast beef.

41:51.500 --> 41:55.708
We didn't make any roast beef.
We made puttanesca sauce.

41:55.792 --> 41:57.167
And homemade pasta.

41:57.250 --> 41:59.625
What? No roast beef?

41:59.708 --> 42:02.417
You didn't tell us you wanted roast beef.

42:02.500 --> 42:03.958
Look at my guests!

42:04.042 --> 42:07.667
They... they can hardly touch
this revolting foreign food.

42:16.125 --> 42:21.958
In agreeing to adopt you,
I became your father.

42:22.042 --> 42:27.583
And as your father,
I am not someone to be trifled with.

42:27.667 --> 42:30.250
You can't go easy on children. They need
to be taught to obey their elders.

42:30.333 --> 42:31.583
You asked them to make dinner.

42:31.667 --> 42:34.083
And all they did was slap together
some disgusting sauce.

42:34.167 --> 42:37.833
That's what happens with wealthy kids.
Money is really a corrupting influence.

42:37.917 --> 42:39.458
Well, let's not get carried away.

42:40.125 --> 42:42.167
Hmm. You're a pretty little one.

42:42.250 --> 42:46.375
I demand that you serve roast beef
to myself and my guests!

42:46.458 --> 42:49.625
We don't have any.
We made pasta puttanesca.

42:50.225 --> 42:52.225
And chocolate puddin for dessert.

42:54.000 --> 42:55.375
- Sunny!
- Put her down.

42:55.458 --> 42:58.833
Alas, poor Sunny.

43:00.000 --> 43:02.917
Let her go!

43:08.667 --> 43:10.167
Oh, oh.

43:19.792 --> 43:23.708
This table is a mess.
There's hardly a place to put down a baby.

43:26.000 --> 43:27.125
Sunny!

43:30.958 --> 43:32.500
We're leaving for rehearsals.

43:32.583 --> 43:34.000
But the baby said
there was chocolate pudding!

43:34.083 --> 43:35.250
Shh.

43:35.333 --> 43:37.833
You children are to clean the table,

43:37.917 --> 43:40.500
and wash the dishes,
and polish the silver,

43:40.583 --> 43:42.875
and rinse out all the wine bottles
for recycling.

43:42.958 --> 43:44.958
And then you are to go
straight to your beds.

43:45.042 --> 43:46.583
You mean our bed?

43:47.292 --> 43:49.333
You've only provided us with one bed.

43:50.750 --> 43:53.083
If you want another bed,

43:53.167 --> 43:56.208
tomorrow you may go into town
and purchase one.

43:56.292 --> 43:58.125
You know perfectly well
we haven't any money.

43:58.208 --> 44:00.083
Hmm. Of course you do.

44:00.167 --> 44:05.000
You three lucky orphans
are inheriting an enormous fortune.

44:05.083 --> 44:07.708
The money our parents left behind
is not to be used until Violet...

44:09.083 --> 44:11.083
Oooh!

44:18.542 --> 44:20.250
The theater awaits.

44:31.208 --> 44:33.583
- Are you all right?
- No.

44:34.708 --> 44:36.708
- This isn't.
- What?

44:37.958 --> 44:40.250
Better than nothing.

44:53.542 --> 44:56.583
There are many, many things
that are better than nothing.

44:56.667 --> 44:59.042
A home-cooked meal is better than nothing.

45:01.208 --> 45:03.917
A roof over one's head
is better than nothing.

45:05.750 --> 45:06.958
And a place to sleep,

45:07.042 --> 45:10.208
even if the bed is very small
and the blanket damp with tears,

45:10.292 --> 45:11.708
is better than nothing.

45:25.250 --> 45:28.250
But being raised in a violent
and sinister environment

45:28.333 --> 45:32.417
by a man more interested in one's fortune
than comfort and well-being

45:32.500 --> 45:34.167
is not better than nothing.

45:34.250 --> 45:35.917
And as the Baudelaires would discover,

45:36.000 --> 45:39.625
there are some things
that even a long night of introspection

45:39.708 --> 45:41.000
cannot change.

46:08.292 --> 46:10.667
<i>The Baudelaire orphans
knew they had to find a way</i>

46:10.750 --> 46:13.250
<i>out of their dreadfully
unfortunate circumstances,</i>

46:13.333 --> 46:17.333
<i>and, perhaps, solve the mystery
of how they ended up in them.</i>

46:21.250 --> 46:24.292
I have the same dedication
to researching and presenting this story

46:24.375 --> 46:26.417
no matter what dangers it puts me in.

46:26.500 --> 46:30.042
Trouble and strife can cover this world
like the dark of night,

46:30.125 --> 46:32.750
or like smoke from a suspicious fire.

46:32.833 --> 46:34.500
And when that happens...

46:49.708 --> 46:53.417
all good, true and decent people
know that it's time to volunteer.

46:56.347 --> 46:58.347
<i>"Baudelaire mansion destroyed"</i>

46:59.917 --> 47:03.083
- I'm worried about the children.
- Me, too.

47:03.167 --> 47:04.792
They're in danger, I know it.

47:04.875 --> 47:06.542
We need to get to them.

47:06.625 --> 47:08.833
We need to get out of here first.

47:08.917 --> 47:12.500
What's that thing Einstein said?

